arch:property.oc:show_val: Full depth and breadth of TR 98
Phase XII: Use levels, robbing and abandonments continue.

Phase X: Site abandonment post major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. Secondary destruction levels occur with the building of intercolumnar walls between the southern columns of the East Colonnade. Parts of the Lower Temenos are converted into areas for industrial activity including the use of the East and West Exedrae for lime manufacture. North of the West Exedra, a large raised platform is constructed from reused limestone and sandstone architectural fragments.

This is the major collapse and debris layer of Trench 98. The sediment is a brown, fine silt (Munsell 7.5 YR 4/6 strong brown), and it is full of architectural fragments, pottery, plaster, and stones. Small amounts of ash, bones, shells, glass, metal, tesserae, and stucco were also found. Some of the architectural fragments were found in close relation to other features, with little apparent disturbance following the original collapse in CE 363. For example, a number of column falls in the north of the trench were found clearly in order. Some even had plaster still joining two column drums together. In the middle of the trench, a concentration of ashlars (currently disappearing into the southern balk) seems to be the remains of the west wall of the West Cryptoporticus West, still maintaining the same order that they had in the wall. As the excavation progressed, different ‘layers’ of collapse were excavated. Though these may suggest that there were multiple periods of collapse, this seems unlikely. The layers were arbitrarily defined, and architectural fragments from one ‘layer’ ran through into lower ‘layers.’ It seems, then, that there was one large collapse, resulting in a mass of collapse with portions of it still aligned as it had been in situ. Further minor collapse and sedimentation then continued for a long period after this initial collapse. The smaller artifacts, such as the bone, pottery, and glass, had an even distribution throughout the trench. Much of the tesserae seems to by Byzantine, showing the long period of sedimentation and deposition of material in locus 3.
Phase XIV: Modern period marked by Bedouin activity and the accumulation of recent debris.

Phase XI: Further collapse post- CE 5th c., possibly the result of the earthquake of CE 512. Major collapses in the Lower Temenos lead to the continued accumulation of fill. At this time the East Colonnade collapses significantly onto a bed of accumulated soil, as does the entablature of the East Exedra.

Phase IX: Major CE 363 earthquake leads to the collapse of the West Colonnade directly on top of the Hexagonal Pavement and into the West Cryptoporticus. The accumulation of early debris during this phase contains large amounts of architectural elements mixed with fill and sedimentation washed over the east perimeter wall. Some collapse is also seen in the south of the East Triple Colonnade.
Phase XIII: Major collapses continue into the Islamic period.
